Lucille Ball was mourned Wednesday in her western New York hometown she left more 
than 50 years ago.  Miss Ball died earlier in Los Angeles.  Pauline Lopus recalled that 
Miss Ball dreamed of fame, worked as an amusement park barker at age 15, and appeared 
in school plays.  After becoming a model, Miss Ball moved to Hollywood in 1933.  She 
kept contacts in Jamestown and was going to visit on May 20 to receive an honorary 
degree from the community college and have a street renamed for her in nearby Celoron, 
where she grew up.  These honors now will be awarded posthumously.</SUM>

